			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&message.id=217966#M217966">154</a> of 206
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 809 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<span><br><blockquote><hr>Eldakka wrote:<br><div><span><br><blockquote><hr>Frodlin wrote:<br><blockquote><div>I find bows that don't have broken strings to be stupid. I think a ranger who uses archery should be motivated to ALWAYS have a fletching kit and repair components along with them at all times.</div></blockquote><hr></blockquote>I fully support this...right after they introduce the need for every weapon using class to carry around sharpening stones to repair nicks in weapons, weapons breaking needing to be repalced/taken to a smith for repairs, reagents for all spells, heals, nukes, buffs etc.<br><br>Yep, once this happens expect my full support.<br></span></div><br><hr></blockquote>I disagree. You don't go far enough. What would be needed is a repair kit. This repair kit would be used to fix anything damaged in battle, weapons (including bows), armor, jewelry, anything. Of course everyone would have to carry repair parts, Links for chain armor, boiled leather for leather armor, steel sheets for plate armor, silk swatches for silk armor, settings for jewelry, etc. Bowstring of course for bows, sharpening stones for bladed weapons, dulling stones (?) for blunt weapons. The mechanics would of this would be quite interesting. Since in general there is usually no warning that a weapon or piece of armor would fail and thus need repairing (even in real life the warning is very short and almost always happen in combat), it would function similar to our fishing pole. Imagine the fun of a ranger in the middle of trueshot having to stop combat to restring his or her bow. Imagine the fun of an enchanter in combat who had to stop in order to fix her robe after it had been burned off him or her by a nuke. Imagine the fun of watching Frodlin tanking the big bad boss MOb when his breastplate suddenly is penetrated and becomes useless (I will chuckle as I am watching this and restringing my bow).<br><br>As for removing EQ from the game entirely? Well, consider the implications of that. EQ as never made an adjustment like that without telling the community &quot;we have to break it before we fix it&quot;. There would be a period of no less than three months and probably more where only the current arrows would be in play without EQ. You could expect rangers to be using the same arrows that all other bow using classes are currently using and nothing better than that. There are some scripts in EQ that have components (if not the entire script) built around ranger archery. During dry period, between the break and the fix, these events will either be undoable or new tactics will have to be created. Essentially these events will not be done unless they are required for something like progression.<br><br>The melee vs archery ranger debate. This subject has been beaten to death in the ranger forums. It is quiet over there now and I see no valid reason to start it up again in this forum. Having said that I have a few things of my own to say.<br>To my PoP and pre-PoP brothers and sisters: SOE has stated that our primary/prefered method of inflicting damage is melee. Get over it.<br>To my post-PoP brothers and sisters: The EP bows (and now Druzzil) are a fact of EQ life just like medding while mounted is. Get over it. Also calling for a removal or even accepting a removal of EQ from the game will essentially nerf all PoP and pre-PoP rangers back to Kunark, is that really what you want?<br><br>The creation of arrows that EQ does not work with or only partially works with. These arrows will have to have significant advantages and be cheap to produce in large quantities for rangers to use them. The current top end arrows are the Mithril, Karana and Class 7 drakes, and depending on what the target is would depend on which is best. A 14 damage arrow would not be significant if it cannot be used with EQ. Yes the other bow using classes would use them (especially if they were cheaper than the silvertip arrows) but rangers would most likely pass on them. Why? The return on investment is not as great for a ranger with EQ as it would be for other bow using classes. A ranger with EQ can easily out damage any other bow class by using 8 damage arrows (they would actually stick with their current arrow) while the other bow class uses the new 14 damage arrows. Bane arrows have been mentioned. Bane weapons are usually weaker than normal weapons except when used against specific MObs. The reason for this is that they are special purpose weapons, meant to be used in a limited set of encounters. An example of this is the weapons used against the emperor in SSRA. Against anything other than shissar they are pathetic. An example of a bane arrow would be: Range 100, Damage 4 +30 vs Summoned (/em snickers). Yes, a even an end-game ranger might fletch and use these things, BUT only if they were in Splitpaw (what anyone would go there for, let alone and end-game player, is beyond me). Most bane arrows would be fletched by rangers at least once (not all rangers fletching all bane arrows) and experimented with. The results would essentially be, &quot;Interesting but hardly worth the effort.&quot; in most cases. Another possiblity for the new arrows that has been brought up are specialty arrows like arrows with DoT's or DD's. I can see it now, Fire arrows, Cold arrows, even Snare and Root arrows. &gt;.&lt;<br>The real problem with these special arrows is not just EQ but ranger archery in general. The arrows themselves have to have a significant advantage over the current arrows (even if only under limited circumstances like a bane arrow) in order for them to be used by rangers (or for that matter anyone). They have to be cheap to make and the materials have to be very easy to acquire for ANYONE to use them. Rangers get double damage on nonmovining nonrooted targets. Rangers get an additional double damage with AM3. Any arrow that would be of a significant benefit to a non-ranger archer would make ranger archery overpowered in that encounter. So the obvious fix is to not only remove EQ from these arrows but also AM3 and ranger double damage vs nonmoving from these arrows. Have fun rogues, warriors and knights, the rangers won't be using them.<br><br><br>Now to the OP. Forget it. SOE has already stated that EQ is &quot;problematic&quot;. It just ain't gonna happen.<br></span><div></div>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							Help! Help! The paranoids are after me!
							</div>
								
