			>
			<div></div><div><span><br><blockquote><hr>Brutul_PB wrote:<br><span><blockquote>gcubed wrote:<br><div></div><div><span><br><blockquote><hr>Aegnor_Cuthalion wrote:<br><div></div><br><blockquote><hr>Brutul_PB wrote:<br><div></div><div><span><br>It was Archery Mastery, not Endless Quiver, that created a demand for high end arrows. </span></div><br><hr></blockquote><br>This is incorrect. Without EQ archery is fairly useless outside of a pulling tool. The amount of arrows that a ranger would go through using archery as a form of damage without EQ is enormous. It just wouldn't be done.<br><hr></blockquote>It would be about the equivalent of a dual wielder's off hand poofing on every swing of the secondary. You would see a lot of warriors, rogues and rangers carrying shields as their secondary. I guess Beastlords and monks would be carrying fire beetle eyes.<br><br><br>Although that wouldn't be such a bad idea. Blacksmithing might become a useful tradeskill. Lets see. it would require an ability to autofeed a secondary weapon, The weapons of course would have to have a good damage/delay ratio. They would have to be fairly cheap to manufacture in mass quantities (say a few gold pieces for each weapon). Yep, would make my blacksmithing profitable. I like this idea. <span><img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-tongue.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0></span><br><br><br><br></span></div><p>Message Edited by gcubed on <span class="date_text">04-14-2006</span><span class="time_text">02:58 PM</span></p><br><hr></blockquote>You guys didn't even read my post. Gcubed, your post is beyond ridiculous, not even worth replying to. What I am talking about is an item, made by fletching, that is instant cast from inventory, has 20 or more charges, reasonably priced, and summons stacks of 100 arrows. That doesn't seem that cumbersome to me for the benefit of rangers being able to do more damage with bows.<br></span><br><div></div><br><hr></blockquote>One. You didn't even read my post or you would have realized it was meant to be rediculous (did you miss the smiley?).<br>Two. If it wasn't worth replying to, then why did you?<br><br>Three. Just what do you expect to charge for something like this in the bazaar? You stated in one of your posts a few gold per arrow to produce. If by a few you mean between 3 and 8 we can expect such an item to cost between 6 platinum and 16 platinum to make. Innitially you might be able to charge around 100 platinum (by price gouging) for each of these. Eventually (quite rapidly) as enough fletchers started selling these things the prices drop to be between 6.5 and 20 platinum. In order for you to keep enough of these things on hand to make any worthwhile amount of money from them they would have to be stackable which also means that they would be stackable in inventory or you would need to keep the prices up. One way to keep prices up is to limit supply. If you limit supply you will essentially reduce archery to a pulling tool or something used by the ramp tank. This will lower your proposed clients to what it is now (warriors and knights) thus lowering the demand and the prices drop again back down to about 6.5 and 20 platinum. You would also an even lower inventory turnover (they won't sell fast). Another way to keep prices up would give this proposed fletch item a very high trivial. Now suddenly this arrow summoner becomes a skill up path. The market will be flooded with them and you will be forced to sell the item at a loss.<br><br><br>In short selling arrows (or your arrow summoning device) will not make anyone rich even if SOE were to totally remove EQ from the game. At best it will keep you in healing potions. At worst you will take a loss every time you create them.<br><br><br></span></div><p>Message Edited by gcubed on <span class="date_text">04-17-2006</span><span class="time_text">01:42 PM</span></p>
